The Development of a Naive Bayes and Neural Network Classifier on Gesture Phase Segmentation:¶

Orginated Dataset: https://archive.ics.uci.edu/ml/datasets/gesture+phase+segmentation

I. Importing packages.¶

This will contain packages that will be used both for the Naive Bayes Classifier and Neural Network Classifier. Graphs will be constructed with the help from matplotlib as well as dervived libraries such as seaborn.

II. Importing dataset.¶

The orginal dataset was composed on 14 individual files: 7 raw files and 7 processed files. There was no master dataset so individual files were download. To get the desired dataset with User A and their three comic strips (1,2,3), I had to converge the individual files below.

In [2]:
data1 = pd.read_csv('a1_va3.csv', header=0)
data2 = pd.read_csv('a2_va3.csv', header=0)
data3 = pd.read_csv('a3_va3.csv', header=0)
data = pd.concat([data1, data2, data3])

Choosing which Naive Bayes Model works best

In [9]:
dataset = data.drop('Phase', axis=1).values
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(dataset, data["Phase"], test_size=0.33, random_state = 42)
In [10]:
BernNB = BernoulliNB(binarize = True)
BernNB.fit(X_train, y_train)
print(BernNB)

bern_y_pred = BernNB.predict(X_test)
BERN_ACC = accuracy_score(y_test, bern_y_pred)
print(BERN_ACC)

In [12]:
GausNB = GaussianNB()
GausNB.fit(X_train, y_train)
print(GausNB)

gaus_y_pred = GausNB.predict(X_test)
GAUS_ACC = accuracy_score(y_test, gaus_y_pred)
print(GAUS_ACC)

GaussianNB(priors=None, var_smoothing=1e-09)
0.515987460815047
In [13]:
NB_labels = ['Bernoulli NB', "Gaussian NB"]
NB_Accuracies = [BERN_ACC, GAUS_ACC]
def NB_accuracy_bar():
    ind = np.arange(len(NB_labels))
    plt.bar(ind, NB_Accuracies)
    plt.xlabel('NB Classifiers', fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy', fontsize = 15)
    plt.xticks(ind, NB_labels, fontsize = 10)
    plt.title('Comparing Accuracy')
    plt.show
NB_accuracy_bar()

We can see through the different accuracy scores that the right Naive Bayes Classifier for this dataset would have to be the Gaussian.

Building a keras model with dense layers:¶

In [17]:
keras.backend.clear_session()
np.random.seed(42)
tf.random.set_seed(42)

model = keras.models.Sequential()

model.add(keras.layers.Dense(100, input_dim=12, activation="sigmoid"))
model.add(keras.layers.Dense(50, activation="sigmoid"))
model.add(keras.layers.Dense(5, activation="softmax"))

model.compile(
    loss='categorical_crossentropy', optimizer= 'rmsprop',
#   optimizer = keras.optimizers.SGD(lr=0.01, nesterov=True),
    metrics=['accuracy'])

history = model.fit(X, y, epochs=100, batch_size = 48)

pd.DataFrame(history.history).plot(figsize=(8, 5))

# To plot pretty figures
%matplotlib inline
import matplotlib as mpl
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
mpl.rc('axes', labelsize=14)
mpl.rc('xtick', labelsize=12)
mpl.rc('ytick', labelsize=12)

y = keras.utils.to_categorical(data['Phase2'])
X = data[attributes].values

X_valid, X_train = X[:50], X[50:]
y_valid, y_train = y[:50], y[50:]

keras.backend.clear_session()
np.random.seed(42)
tf.random.set_seed(42)

model = keras.models.Sequential()

model.add(keras.layers.Dense(100, input_dim=12, activation="relu"))
model.add(keras.layers.Dense(50, activation="relu"))
model.add(keras.layers.Dense(5, activation="softmax"))

model.compile(
    loss='categorical_crossentropy',
    optimizer= 'rmsprop',
#    optimizer = keras.optimizers.RMSprop(lr=0.01, rho=0.9),
    metrics=['accuracy'])

history = model.fit(X_train, y_train, 
                    validation_data = (X_valid, y_valid),
                    epochs=100, batch_size = 50, verbose = 0)

pd.DataFrame(history.history).plot(figsize=(8, 5))
plt.grid(True)

label = ['Bernoulli NB', "Gaussian NB", "Neural Network"]
Accuracy = [BERN_ACC, GAUS_ACC, NN_acc]
def plot_accuracy_bar():
    index = np.arange(len(label))
    plt.bar(index, Accuracy)
    plt.xlabel('ML Models', fontsize = 15)
    plt.ylabel('Accuracy', fontsize = 15)
    plt.xticks(index, label, fontsize = 10)
    plt.title('Comparing Accuracy')
    plt.show
plot_accuracy_bar()
